HIGH NONCE_REUSE_DETECTION: Missing nonce reuse detection in cryptographic operations (particularly in AES-GCM and ChaCha20-Poly1305) can lead to catastrophic security failures where reuse of the same nonce with the same key allows attackers to recover the authentication key and potentially decrypt or forge messages.

Impact:
- Complete breakdown of authentication and confidentiality
- Potential recovery of encryption key
- Ability to forge arbitrary messages
- Decryption of intercepted communications
- Catastrophic failure of cryptographic guarantees

Fix:
1. Implement nonce tracking to detect reuse:
```rust
// BEFORE:
fn encrypt_with_gcm(key: &[u8; 32], nonce: &[u8; 12], plaintext: &[u8]) -> Result<Vec<u8>, CryptoError> {
    let cipher = GcmAes256::new_key_from_slice(key)?;
    cipher.encrypt(nonce.into(), plaintext.as_ref())
        .map_err(|_| CryptoError::EncryptionFailed)
}

// AFTER:
struct AeadEncryptor {
    key: [u8; 32],
    used_nonces: Mutex<FxHashSet<[u8; 12]>>,  // Track used nonces
    cipher: GcmAes256,
}

impl AeadEncryptor {
    fn new(key: [u8; 32]) -> Self {
        let cipher = GcmAes256::new_key_from_slice(key)
            .expect("Valid key length");
        AeadEncryptor {
            key,
            used_nonces: Mutex::new(FxHashSet::default()),
            cipher,
        }
    }

    fn encrypt(&self, nonce: &[u8; 12], plaintext: &[u8]) -> Result<Vec<u8>, CryptoError> {
        // Check for nonce reuse
        let mut used_nonces = self.used_nonces.lock().map_err(|_| {
            CryptoError::LockPoisoned
        })?;

        if !used_nonces.insert(*nonce) {
            return Err(CryptoError::NonceReuseDetected);
        }

        // Perform encryption
        self.cipher.encrypt(nonce.into(), plaintext.as_ref())
            .map_err(|_| CryptoError::EncryptionFailed)
    }
}
```

